urname is found predominantly in the south and southwestern parts of the country. Compare   Well   1.","English: nickname from Middle English <i>iwil</i>, <i>wil(l)e</i> ‘agreeable, pleasing’."]},{"name":"Willson","meanings":["English (eastern): variant of   Wilson  ."]}]},{"name":"Marmaduke","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of uncertain derivation. It is generally held to be an Anglicized form of the Old Irish name <i>Mael-Maedóc</i> ‘devotee of Maedóc’. The name <i>Maedóc</i> was borne by various early Irish saints, most notably a 6th-century abbot of Clonmore and a 7th-century bishop of Ferns.  Mael-Maedóc Ó Morgair  (  1095–1148 ) was a reformer of the Church in Ireland and a friend of Bernard of Clairvaux. However, the modern Gaelic form (from  <i>c.</i>1200 ) is <i>Maol-Maodhóg</i> (pronounced ‘mul-<b>may</b>-og’), so that the name would have had to have been borrowed into English before this loss of the <i>d</i>. <i>Marmaduke</i> has never been common except in Yorkshire, where for example it was bourne by  Marmaduke Huby , abbot of Fountains, (  1495–1526 ). Its most notable bearer in recent times has been  Marmaduke Hussey  (  1923–2006 ), a former chairman of the governors of the BBC."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":2,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":11,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Sir Marmaduke Wilson was born in October 1546, in Hornsea, Yorkshire, England. He had at least 1 daughter with Lady Catherine Holme. He died on 11 July 1568, in Everingham, Yorkshire, England, at the age of 21."},"et":{"October 1546–11 July 1568":"oktoober 1546–11. juuli 1568","1544–1634":"1544–1634","1559–1639":"1559–1639","1546–1568":"1546–1568","1558":"1558","1568":"1568","1546":"1546","1634":"1634","11 July 1568":"11. juuli 1568","1544":"1544","October 1546":"oktoober 1546","1639":"1639","1549":"1549","1559":"1559","Hipperholme, Yorkshire, England":"Hipperholme, Yorkshire, England","Everingham, Yorkshire, England":"Everingham, Yorkshire, England","Hornsea, Yorkshire, England":"Hornsea, Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"October 1546–11 July 1568":"lokakuu 1546–11. heinäkuuta 1568","1544–1634":"1544–1634","1559–1639":"1559–1639","1546–1568":"1546–1568","1558":"1558","1568":"1568","1546":"1546","1634":"1634","11 July 1568":"11. heinäkuuta 1568","1544":"1544","October 1546":"lokakuu 1546","1639":"1639","1549":"1549","1559":"1559","Hipperholme, Yorkshire, England":"Hipperholme, Yorkshire, England","Everingham, Yorkshire, England":"Everingham, Yorkshire, England","Hornsea, Yorkshire, England":"Hornsea, Yorkshire, England"},"fr":{"October 1546–11 July 1568":"octobre 1546–11 juillet 1568","1544–1634":"1544–1634","1559–1639":"1559–1639","1546–1568":"1546–1568","1558":"1558","1568":"1568","1546":"1546","1634":"1634","11 July 1568":"11 juillet 1568","1544":"1544","October 1546":"octobre 1546","1639":"1639","1549":"1549","1559":"1559","Hipperholme, Yorkshire, England":"Hipperholme, Everwyck, Angleterre","Everingham, Yorkshire, England":"Everingham, Everwyck, Angleterre","